TY  - JOUR
AB  - "Job-conscious" unionism is practiced not only by skilled trade but also by industrial unions composed primarily of semi-skilled and unskilled workers. This thesis is tested by an analysis of cases on shop discipline, shop practices and trade customs decided by the Chicago Trade Board in the period from 1919 to 1929. These cases concern questions of control of the opportunity to work and the conditions of tenure in the job--the fundamental bases of customary job control. The job security of the Chicago clothing workers is not fundamentally different from that of many of the skilled trade unions, although it may bear a closer relation to the economic efficiency of the industry than is occasionally found elsewhere.
