TY  - JOUR
AB  - Multiplication of classifications of public expenditures has resulted in confusion and much argument as to which is best. This is due to failure to realize that there will be as many proper classifications as there are possible angles of approach to the subject. No classification should be criticised except with reference to its particular purpose. Furthermore, no classification (except those for budgetary purposes) should be condemned because of difficulty in fitting specific items of expenditure into certain set classes. The classificatory groups are necessarily arbitrary and fixed, while the facts themselves are fluid and dynamic. Every classification that sheds new light on the subject is needed. It is only necessary that we see the various classifications in relation to each other and to the question as a whole.
